File: platform/browser-extension/src/tab-state.ts, lines 51-77. Currently uses a bare Promise.race with an untracked setTimeout:

```ts
const results = await Promise.race([
  chrome.scripting.executeScript({ ... }),
  new Promise<null>(resolve => setTimeout(() => resolve(null), IS_READY_TIMEOUT_MS)),
]);
```

The fix: extract the timer ID so it can be cleared. A clean pattern is to wrap both competitors in a helper that tracks the timer:

```ts
let timerId: ReturnType<typeof setTimeout> | undefined;
try {
  const results = await Promise.race([
    chrome.scripting.executeScript({ ... }),
    new Promise<null>(resolve => {
      timerId = setTimeout(() => resolve(null), IS_READY_TIMEOUT_MS);
    }),
  ]);
  // ... existing result handling ...
} finally {
  if (timerId !== undefined) clearTimeout(timerId);
}
```

Alternatively, use AbortSignal.timeout if available, but the manual clearTimeout approach is simpler and more consistent with the rest of the codebase. The key constraint is that the external behavior must remain identical — same return type, same timeout value, same logging on timeout.

File: platform/browser-extension/src/tab-state.ts, lines 124-167. Currently, sendTabSyncAll does:
1. Compute all plugin states in parallel (line 129-131) — this is fine
2. lastKnownState.clear() (line 144) — this bypasses withPluginLock
3. lastKnownState.set() in a loop (lines 145-147) — also bypasses withPluginLock

Meanwhile, notifyAffectedPlugins (line 209-227) reads and writes lastKnownState inside withPluginLock. If a Chrome tab event fires during sendTabSyncAll's execution, notifyAffectedPlugins for that plugin could read lastKnownState after clear() but before the sync repopulates it, seeing no previous state and potentially sending a redundant notification.

The fix: after computing all states, write each plugin's state through withPluginLock:

```ts
// After computing entries from Promise.allSettled:
const pluginNamesInSync = new Set<string>();
await Promise.all(
  entries.map(([pluginName, stateInfo]) => {
    pluginNamesInSync.add(pluginName);
    return withPluginLock(pluginName, async () => {
      lastKnownState.set(pluginName, stateInfo.state);
    });
  }),
);
// Clean up plugins no longer in the index
for (const key of lastKnownState.keys()) {
  if (!pluginNamesInSync.has(key)) {
    lastKnownState.delete(key);
    pluginLocks.delete(key);
  }
}
```

The cleanup loop replaces the old lastKnownState.clear() — it only removes entries for plugins that no longer exist in the index, rather than clearing everything and repopulating. This avoids the window where the cache is empty.

The server message (tab.syncAll) and side panel forwarding should remain after the lock writes, outside the lock callbacks, since they are outbound-only and do not read lastKnownState.
